<text>
<body>

<div type="description" n="monument">
<head>Description of Monument</head>
<p>A <rs type="material" key="marmor">white marble</rs> columnar <rs type="objectType"><rs type="objectType">statue base</rs> shaft</rs> (H. approx <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="height">1.30</measure>, diam. <measure dim="diameter" type="length">0.55</measure>), broken in two.</p>
</div>

<div type="description" n="text">
<head>Description of Text</head>
<p><rs type="execution" key="scalpro">Inscribed</rs> on the face: the surface is chipped (as it already was in 1904) at the upper left corner of the inscription.</p>
</div>

<div type="description" n="letters">
<head>Description of Letters</head>
<p>Av. <measure type="length" unit="metre" dim="height" precision="circa">0.03</measure>; slightly elongated; decorative serifs.</p>
</div>

<div type="description" n="date">
<head>Date</head>
<p><date notAfter="0386" exact="both" notBefore="0383">A.D. 383-386</date> (<rs type="criteria">prosopography</rs>, <rs type="criteria">titulature</rs>).</p>
</div>

<div n="text" lang="grc" type="edition">
<head lang="en">Edition</head>
<ab type="official-secul"><lb n="1"/><w lemma="ὁ"><supplied reason="lost">τ</supplied>ὴν</w> <w lemma="αἰώνιος">αἰωνίαν</w> <w lemma="καί">καὶ</w> <rs type="dignity" key="theophilestatos"><w lemma="θεοφιλής">θεοφιλε<lb n="2" type="worddiv"/><supplied reason="lost">σ</supplied>τάτην</w></rs> <rs type="dignity" key="augusta"><persName type="emperor"><name reg="Αὔγουστα">Αὔγουσταν</name></persName></rs> <space extent="1" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/> <persName key="AeliaFlaccilla" type="emperor" full="yes"><name reg="Αἰλία">Αἰλίαν</name><lb n="3"/><name reg="Φλαβία">Φλαβίαν</name> <space extent="1" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/> <name reg="Φλακκίλλα">Φλακ<unclear reason="damage">κ</unclear>ίλλαν</name></persName><lb n="4"/><w lemma="ὁ">τὴν</w> <rs type="official-secul" key="despot"><w lemma="δέσποινα">δέσποιναν</w></rs> <w lemma="ὁ">τῆς</w> <w lemma="οἰμουμένη">οἰκουμένης</w><lb n="5"/><rs type="subject" key="koinon"><w lemma="Κᾶρ">Κᾶρες</w></rs> <w lemma="ἱδρύω">ἵδρυσαν</w> <w lemma="ἐν">ἐν</w> <w lemma="ὁ">τῇ</w> <space extent="1" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/> <w lemma="ἑαυτοῦ">ἑαυτῶν</w><lb n="6"/><space extent="unknown" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/> <rs type="subject" key="capital"><w lemma="μητρόπολις">μητροπόλει</w></rs> <space extent="unknown" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/><lb n="7"/><space extent="unknown" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/> <g type="cross"/> <space extent="unknown" unit="character" dim="horizontal"/>
</ab>
</div>

<div type="apparatus">
<head>Apparatus</head>
<p>1.7. The cross, faintly cut on the base below the inscription, was first observed by the Roberts; it is not certainly associated with the text.</p>
</div>

<div type="translation">
<head>Translation</head>
<p>The Carians set up in their own metropolis the <supplied reason="subaudible">statue of </supplied> the eternal Augusta, most dear to God, Aelia Flavia Flacilla, the mistress of the inhabited world.</p>
</div>

<div type="commentary">
<head>Commentary</head>
<p>See discussion at <xref type="eAla-text" n="III.21">III.21</xref>.</p>
</div>

<div type="history" n="locations"><head>Locations</head><p> <rs type="found"><rs key="HadrBath" type="monuList">Hadrianic Baths, East Court</rs>: <foreign lang="fr">Thermes, façade</foreign> (Gaudin). At the north side of the east court of the baths, next to <xref type="inscription" n="25" href="050217">5.217</xref>.</rs> <rs type="origLocation">Findspot.</rs> <rs type="lastLocation">Findspot (1994).</rs>. </p></div>





<div type="history" n="record">
<head>History of Recording</head>
<p>Recorded by <rs type="visitor" key="gaudin">Gaudin</rs> (104) and noted by Boulanger (Notebook A, 43); the stone appears subsequently to have broken into two fragments, of which the lower was recorded by <rs type="visitor" key="robert">J. and L. Robert</rs> in <date value="1946" notBefore="1946" notAfter="1946" exact="both">1946</date>. Both fragments were recorded by the NYU expedition.</p>
</div>

